# Class: obo:APOLLO_SV_00000470 (probability)

AnnotationAssertion(obo:IAO_0000115 obo:APOLLO_SV_00000470 "A data item that is about a proposition and has a numeric value between 0 and 1, inclusive, that is the output of some process of inference, such that 1) logical falsehoods and logical truths are assigned a value of 0 and 1, respectively, while contingent propositions are assigned some intermediate value; and 2) the process of inference conforms with rules for the calculation of probabilities, and that any interpretation of probability must specify the extent to which probabilities might be used to constrain the degrees of belief of rational agents."@en)
AnnotationAssertion(obo:IAO_0000117 obo:APOLLO_SV_00000470 "Matthew Diller")
AnnotationAssertion(obo:IAO_0000117 obo:APOLLO_SV_00000470 "William R. Hogan")
AnnotationAssertion(obo:IAO_0000600 obo:APOLLO_SV_00000470 "A data item that is about a proposition and has a numeric value between 0 and 1, inclusive, that is the output of some process of inference, such that 1) logical falsehoods and logical truths are assigned a value of 0 and 1, respectively, while contingent propositions are assigned some intermediate value; and 2) the process of inference conforms with rules for the calculation of probabilities, and that any interpretation of probability must specify the extent to which probabilities might be used to constrain the degrees of belief of rational agents."@en)
AnnotationAssertion(apollo_sv:APOLLO_SV_0000040 obo:APOLLO_SV_00000470 "Probability")
AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:comment obo:APOLLO_SV_00000470 "The first criterion is derived from Kolmogorov's Probability Calculus, while the second is derived from Salmon's Admissibility and Applicability Criteria of Adequacy. Salmon's ascertainability criterion is subsumed by the definition for 'data item'."@en)
AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:label obo:APOLLO_SV_00000470 "probability"@en)
SubClassOf(obo:APOLLO_SV_00000470 obo:IAO_0000027)

